<p class="Endnotes"><span id="endnote-011"><a class="_idEndnoteAnchor _idGenColorInherit" href="#endnote-011-backlink">11</a><span class="superscript CharOverride-9"> </span><span class="CharOverride-7">Examples of big battles include White Mountain (1620), Breitenfeld (1631), Lützen (1632), Nördlingen (1634), Wittstock (1636), and Rocroi (1643). Armies consisted mostly of foreign mercenaries. For example, the majority of Sweden&rsquo;s military was mercenary, a significant number given that Sweden was a military superpower at the time and King Gustavus Adolphus was one of the great innovators of maneuver warfare. </span><span class="CharOverride-10">At the Battle of Breitenfeld, only 20 percent of Sweden&rsquo;s army consisted of Swedes, and at the Battle of Lutzen the figure was 18 percent. This was typical of the time. See Geoffrey Parker, </span><span class="CharOverride-11">Europe in Crisis, 1598&ndash;1648</span><span class="CharOverride-10"> (Oxford: Wiley-Blackwell, 2001), 17.</span></span></p>

<p class="Endnotes"><span id="endnote-012"><a class="_idEndnoteAnchor _idGenColorInherit" href="#endnote-012-backlink">12</a><span class="superscript CharOverride-9"> </span><span class="CharOverride-7">Franco Sacchetti, </span><span class="CharOverride-8">Il Trecentonovelle</span><span class="CharOverride-7">, novella CLXXXI (Torino: Einaudi, 1970), 528&ndash;529. For more on this period, see William Caferro, </span><span class="CharOverride-8">John Hawkwood: An English Mercenary in Fourteenth-Century Italy</span><span class="CharOverride-7"> (Baltimore, MD: Johns Hopkins University Press, 2006).</span></span></p>

<p class="Endnotes"><span id="endnote-013"><a class="_idEndnoteAnchor _idGenColorInherit" href="#endnote-013-backlink">13</a><span class="superscript CharOverride-9"> </span><span class="CharOverride-7">For instance, in 1919 the eminent German sociologist Max Weber defined the </span><span class="CharOverride-8">state</span><span class="CharOverride-7"> as &ldquo;a human community that (successfully) claims the monopoly of the legitimate use of physical force within a given territory.&rdquo; This definition remains widely used today, and states that cannot maintain a monopoly of force and endure civil war or frequent violent crime are routinely described as &ldquo;weak,&rdquo; &ldquo;fragile,&rdquo; or &ldquo;failed&rdquo; states. See H.H. Gerth and C. Wright Mills, eds., </span><span class="CharOverride-8">From Max Weber: Essays in Sociology</span><span class="CharOverride-7"> (London: Routledge, 2003), 77&ndash;128.</span></span></p>

<p class="Endnotes"><span id="endnote-014"><a class="_idEndnoteAnchor _idGenColorInherit" href="#endnote-014-backlink">14</a><span class="superscript CharOverride-9"> </span><span class="CharOverride-7">The Katanga secession and Congo Crisis of 1960&ndash;1968 attracted hundreds of mercenaries, some known as Les Affreux (The Frightfuls), and included the Irishman &ldquo;Mad&rdquo; Mike Hoare and the Frenchman Bob Denard. Their exploits informed the novel </span><span class="CharOverride-8">The Wild Geese</span><span class="CharOverride-7"> by Daniel Carney and the 1978 film by the same name, for which Hoare was a technical advisor. There is also the film </span><span class="CharOverride-8">The Dogs of War</span><span class="CharOverride-7"> (1980), based on a Frederick Forsyth novel, inspired by the life of Denard. For a modern account of mercenaries, the author recommends the Tom Locke novel series (William Morrow).</span></span></p>

